  "text": "Preparation of bacterial cells and ECPs. All 4 Aeromonas hydrophila isolates were grown in tryptic soy broth (TSB) (Difco) at 28°C for 18 to 24 h. The concentration (colony-forming units, CFU, ml -1 ) of A. hydro phila used in this study was determined through serial dilutions, as described previously [CITATION_1] . For each of the 4 isolates, the procedure was as follows. To prepare A. hydrophila cells without their ECPs, 100 ml of broth culture, with an optical density (OD) of 1.0 at 540 nm, was centrifuged at 6000 × g for 20 min. After removing the supernatant fluid containing ECPs, the bacterial cells were resuspended in 100 ml of fresh TSB and used for immersion or injection experiments. The supernatant fluid of the broth culture was then sterilized with a filter of pore size 0.22 µm (Corning Disposable Vacuum Filtration Systems, Cole-Parmer). The sterilized supernatant was used as a source of ECPs in bath immersion and injection experiments in order to study their toxicity. The protein concentration of the ECPs from each isolate was then determined using BCA Protein assay (Pierce). Equal amounts of ECPs from each isolate were used in the toxicity studies.",
